Here is a Java code that uses the two-pointer method to reverse an array:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        reverseArray(arr);
        for (int i : arr) {
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
    }

    public static void reverseArray(int[] arr) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.length - 1;
        while (left < right) {
            // Swap elements at left and right indices
            int temp = arr[left];
            arr[left] = arr[right];
            arr[right] = temp;
            left++;
            right--;
        }
    }
}
```

This code uses two pointers, `left` and `right`, starting from both ends of the array. It swaps the elements at the `left` and `right` indices, and then moves the pointers towards the center of the array. This process continues until the `left` pointer meets or crosses the `right` pointer, at which point the array is reversed.
